\subsection{\href{https://beta.lmfdb.org/knowledge/show/ec.mordell_weil_group}{Mordell-Weil group}}
\begin{definition}\label{ec.mordell_weil_group}
\uses{ag.abelian_variety,ag.mordell_weil,ec,nf}
For an \hyperref[ec]{elliptic curve} $E$ defined over a field $K$, the \textbf{Mordell-Weil group} of $E/K$ is the group $E(K)$ of $K$-rational points of $E$. It is a finitely-generated Abelian group.

This is a special case of the \hyperref[ag.mordell_weil]{Mordell-Weil group of an abelian variety}.

The \hyperref[ec.mordell_weil_theorem]{Mordell-Weil Theorem}, first proved by Mordell for elliptic curves defined over $\Q$ and  later generalized by Weil to \hyperref[ag.abelian_variety]{abelian varieties} $A$ over general \hyperref[nf]{number fields} $K$, states that, if $K$ is a number field, then $A(K)$ is a finitely generated abelian group. Its \hyperref[ec.rank]{rank} is called the \textbf{Mordell-Weil rank} of $A$ over $K$.

The Mordell-Weil theorem implies in particular that the \hyperref[ec.torsion_subgroup]{torsion subgroup} $E(K)_{\mathrm{tor}}$ of $E(K)$ is finite, and thus that the \hyperref[ec.torsion_order]{torsion order} of $E$, one of the \hyperref[ec.bsdconjecture]{BSD}  invariants, is finite.
\end{definition}
